#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:0
msgid "Packaging Existing Software With Nix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:0
msgid "Nix, packaging"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:9
msgid "Packaging existing software with Nix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:11
msgid ""
"One of Nix's primary use-cases is in addressing common difficulties "
"encountered with packaging software, such as specifying and obtaining "
"dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:13
msgid ""
"In the long term, Nix helps tremendously with alleviating such problems. But "
"when *first* packaging existing software with Nix, it's common to encounter "
"errors that seem inscrutable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:16
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:18
msgid ""
"In this tutorial, you'll create your first [Nix derivations](https://nix.dev/"
"manual/nix/stable/language/derivations) to package C/C++ software, taking "
"advantage of the [Nixpkgs Standard Environment](https://nixos.org/manual/"
"nixpkgs/stable/#part-stdenv) (`stdenv`), which automates much of the work "
"involved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:20
msgid "What will you learn?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:22
msgid ""
"The tutorial begins with `hello`, an implementation of \"hello world\" which "
"only requires dependencies already provided by `stdenv`. Next, you will "
"build more complex packages with their own dependencies, leading you to use "
"additional derivation features."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:25
msgid ""
"You'll encounter and address Nix error messages, build failures, and a host "
"of other issues, developing your iterative debugging techniques along the "
"way."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:27
msgid "What do you need?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:29
msgid "Familiarity with the Unix shell and plain text editors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:30
msgid ""
"You should be confident with [reading the Nix language](reading-nix-"
"language). Feel free to go back and work through the tutorial first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:32
msgid "How long does it take?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:34
msgid "Going through all the steps carefully will take around 60 minutes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:36
msgid "Your first package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:39
msgid ""
"<!--\n"
"TODO: link to the Nix manual glossary entry once it's in a released build:\n"
"https://hydra.nixos.org/job/nix/master/build.x86_64-linux/latest/download/"
"manual/glossary.html#package\n"
"-->\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:43
msgid ""
"A _package_ is a loosely defined concept that refers to either a collection "
"of files and other data, or a {term}`Nix expression` representing such a "
"collection before it comes into being. Packages in Nixpkgs have a "
"conventional structure, allowing them to be discovered in searches and "
"composed in environments alongside other packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:46
msgid ""
"For the purposes of this tutorial, a \"package\" is a Nix language function "
"that will evaluate to a derivation. It will enable you or others to produce "
"an artifact for practical use, as a consequence of having \"packaged "
"existing software with Nix\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:50
msgid "To start, consider this skeleton derivation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:52
msgid ""
"{ stdenv }:\n"
"\n"
"stdenv.mkDerivation {\t}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:58
msgid ""
"This is a function which takes an attribute set containing `stdenv`, and "
"produces a derivation (which currently does nothing)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:60
msgid "A package function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:62
msgid ""
"GNU Hello is an implementation of the \"hello world\" program, with source "
"code accessible [from the GNU Project's FTP server](https://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/"
"hello/)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:64
msgid ""
"To begin, add a `pname` attribute to the set passed to `mkDerivation`. Every "
"package needs a name and a version, and Nix will throw `error: derivation "
"name missing` without one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:67
msgid ""
"\n"
"stdenv.mkDerivation {\n"
"+ pname = \"hello\";\n"
"+ version = \"2.12.1\";\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:75
msgid ""
"Next, you will declare a dependency on the latest version of `hello`, and "
"instruct Nix to use `fetchzip` to download the [source code archive](https://"
"ftp.gnu.org/gnu/hello/hello-2.12.1.tar.gz)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:78
msgid ""
"`fetchzip` can fetch [more archives](https://nixos.org/manual/nixpkgs/stable/"
"#fetchurl) than just zip files!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:81
msgid ""
"The hash cannot be known until after the archive has been downloaded and "
"unpacked. Nix will complain if the hash supplied to `fetchzip` is incorrect. "
"Set the `hash` attribute to an empty string and then use the resulting error "
"message to determine the correct hash:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:85
msgid ""
"# hello.nix\n"
"{\n"
"  stdenv,\n"
"  fetchzip,\n"
"}:\n"
"\n"
"stdenv.mkDerivation {\n"
"  pname = \"hello\";\n"
"  version = \"2.12.1\";\n"
"\n"
"  src = fetchzip {\n"
"    url = \"https://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/hello/hello-2.12.1.tar.gz\";\n"
"    sha256 = \"\";\n"
"  };\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:103
msgid ""
"Save this file to `hello.nix` and run `nix-build` to observe your first "
"build failure:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:105
msgid ""
"$ nix-build hello.nix\n"
"error: cannot evaluate a function that has an argument without a value "
"('stdenv')\n"
"       Nix attempted to evaluate a function as a top level expression; in\n"
"       this case it must have its arguments supplied either by default\n"
"       values, or passed explicitly with '--arg' or '--argstr'. See\n"
"       https://nix.dev/manual/nix/stable/language/constructs."
"html#functions.\n"
"\n"
"       at /home/nix-user/hello.nix:3:3:\n"
"\n"
"            2| {\n"
"            3|   stdenv,\n"
"             |   ^\n"
"            4|   fetchzip,\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:121
msgid ""
"Problem: the expression in `hello.nix` is a *function*, which only produces "
"its intended output if it is passed the correct *arguments*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:123
msgid "Building with `nix-build`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:125
msgid ""
"`stdenv` is available from [`nixpkgs`](https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/), "
"which must be imported with another Nix expression in order to pass it as an "
"argument to this derivation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:127
msgid ""
"The recommended way to do this is to create a `default.nix` file in the same "
"directory as `hello.nix`, with the following contents:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:129
msgid ""
"# default.nix\n"
"let\n"
"  nixpkgs = fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/tarball/"
"nixos-24.05\";\n"
"  pkgs = import nixpkgs { config = {}; overlays = []; };\n"
"in\n"
"{\n"
"  hello = pkgs.callPackage ./hello.nix { };\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:140
msgid ""
"This allows you to run `nix-build -A hello` to realize the derivation in "
"`hello.nix`, similar to the current convention used in Nixpkgs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:143
msgid ""
"`callPackage` automatically passes attributes from `pkgs` to the given "
"function, if they match attributes required by that function's argument "
"attribute set. In this case, `callPackage` will supply `stdenv` and "
"`fetchzip` to the function defined in `hello.nix`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:146
msgid "The tutorial [](./callpackage.md) goes into detail on how this works."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:149
msgid "Now run the `nix-build` command with the new argument:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:151
msgid ""
"$ nix-build -A hello\n"
"error: hash mismatch in fixed-output derivation '/nix/store/"
"pd2kiyfa0c06giparlhd1k31bvllypbb-source.drv':\n"
"         specified: sha256-AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA=\n"
"            got:    sha256-1kJjhtlsAkpNB7f6tZEs+dbKd8z7KoNHyDHEJ0tmhnc=\n"
"error: 1 dependencies of derivation '/nix/store/"
"b4mjwlv73nmiqgkdabsdjc4zq9gnma1l-hello-2.12.1.drv' failed to build\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:159
msgid "Finding the file hash"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:160
msgid ""
"As expected, the incorrect file hash caused an error, and Nix helpfully "
"provided the correct one. In `hello.nix`, replace the empty string with the "
"correct hash:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:163
msgid ""
"# hello.nix\n"
"{\n"
"  stdenv,\n"
"  fetchzip,\n"
"}:\n"
"\n"
"stdenv.mkDerivation {\n"
"  pname = \"hello\";\n"
"  version = \"2.12.1\";\n"
"\n"
"  src = fetchzip {\n"
"    url = \"https://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/hello/hello-2.12.1.tar.gz\";\n"
"    sha256 = \"sha256-1kJjhtlsAkpNB7f6tZEs+dbKd8z7KoNHyDHEJ0tmhnc=\";\n"
"  };\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:181
msgid "Now run the previous command again:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:183
msgid ""
"$ nix-build -A hello\n"
"this derivation will be built:\n"
"  /nix/store/rbq37s3r76rr77c7d8x8px7z04kw2mk7-hello.drv\n"
"building '/nix/store/rbq37s3r76rr77c7d8x8px7z04kw2mk7-hello.drv'...\n"
"...\n"
"configuring\n"
"...\n"
"configure: creating ./config.status\n"
"config.status: creating Makefile\n"
"...\n"
"building\n"
"... <many more lines omitted>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:197
msgid "Great news: the derivation built successfully!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:199
msgid ""
"The console output shows that `configure` was called, which produced a "
"`Makefile` that was then used to build the project. It wasn't necessary to "
"write any build instructions in this case because the `stdenv` build system "
"is based on [GNU Autoconf](https://www.gnu.org/software/autoconf/), which "
"automatically detected the structure of the project directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:202
msgid "Build result"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:203
msgid "Check your working directory for the result:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:205
msgid ""
"$ ls\n"
"default.nix hello.nix  result\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:210
msgid ""
"This `result` is a [symbolic link](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/"
"Symbolic_link) to a Nix store location containing the built binary; you can "
"call `./result/bin/hello` to execute this program:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:212
msgid ""
"$ ./result/bin/hello\n"
"Hello, world!\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:217
msgid ""
"Congratulations, you have successfully packaged your first program with Nix!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:219
msgid ""
"Next, you'll package another piece of software with external-to-`stdenv` "
"dependencies that present new challenges, requiring you to make use of more "
"`mkDerivation` features."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:221
msgid "A package with dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:223
msgid ""
"Now you will package a somewhat more complicated program, [`icat`](https://"
"github.com/atextor/icat), which allows you to render images in your terminal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:225
msgid ""
"Change the `default.nix` from the previous section by adding a new attribute "
"for `icat`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:227
msgid ""
"# default.nix\n"
"let\n"
"  nixpkgs = fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/tarball/"
"nixos-24.05\";\n"
"  pkgs = import nixpkgs { config = {}; overlays = []; };\n"
"in\n"
"{\n"
"  hello = pkgs.callPackage ./hello.nix { };\n"
"  icat = pkgs.callPackage ./icat.nix { };\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:239
msgid ""
"Copy `hello.nix` to a new file `icat.nix`, and update the `pname` and "
"`version` attributes in that file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:241
msgid ""
"# icat.nix\n"
"{\n"
"  stdenv,\n"
"  fetchzip,\n"
"}:\n"
"\n"
"stdenv.mkDerivation {\n"
"  pname = \"icat\";\n"
"  version = \"v0.5\";\n"
"\n"
"  src = fetchzip {\n"
"    # ...\n"
"  };\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:258
msgid ""
"Now to download the source code. `icat`'s upstream repository is hosted on "
"[GitHub](https://github.com/atextor/icat), so you should replace the "
"previous [source fetcher](https://nixos.org/manual/nixpkgs/stable/#chap-pkgs-"
"fetchers). This time you will use [`fetchFromGitHub`](https://nixos.org/"
"manual/nixpkgs/stable/#fetchfromgithub) instead of `fetchzip`, by updating "
"the argument attribute set to the function accordingly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:262
msgid ""
"# icat.nix\n"
"{\n"
"  stdenv,\n"
"  fetchFromGitHub,\n"
"}:\n"
"\n"
"stdenv.mkDerivation {\n"
"  pname = \"icat\";\n"
"  version = \"v0.5\";\n"
"\n"
"  src = fetchFromGitHub {\n"
"    # ...\n"
"  };\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:279
msgid "Fetching source from GitHub"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:280
msgid ""
"While `fetchzip` required `url` and `sha256` arguments, more are needed for "
"[`fetchFromGitHub`](https://nixos.org/manual/nixpkgs/stable/"
"#fetchfromgithub)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:282
msgid ""
"The source URL is `https://github.com/atextor/icat`, which already gives the "
"first two arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:283
msgid "`owner`: the name of the account controlling the repository"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:285
msgid "owner = \"atextor\";\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:288
msgid "`repo`: the name of the repository to fetch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:290
msgid "repo = \"icat\";\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:294
msgid ""
"Navigate to the project's [Tags page](https://github.com/atextor/icat/tags) "
"to find a suitable [Git revision](https://git-scm.com/docs/revisions) "
"(`rev`), such as the Git commit hash or tag (e.g. `v1.0`) corresponding to "
"the release you want to fetch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:296
msgid "In this case, the latest release tag is `v0.5`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:298
msgid ""
"As in the `hello` example, a hash must also be supplied. This time, instead "
"of using the empty string and letting `nix-build` report the correct one in "
"an error, you can fetch the correct hash in the first place with the `nix-"
"prefetch-url` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:301
msgid ""
"You need the SHA256 hash of the *contents* of the tarball (as opposed to the "
"hash of the tarball file itself). Therefore pass the `--unpack` and `--type "
"sha256` arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:304
msgid ""
"$ nix-prefetch-url --unpack https://github.com/atextor/icat/archive/refs/"
"tags/v0.5.tar.gz --type sha256\n"
"path is '/nix/store/p8jl1jlqxcsc7ryiazbpm7c1mqb6848b-v0.5.tar.gz'\n"
"0wyy2ksxp95vnh71ybj1bbmqd5ggp13x3mk37pzr99ljs9awy8ka\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:310
msgid "Set the correct hash for `fetchFromGitHub`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:312
msgid ""
"# icat.nix\n"
"{\n"
"  stdenv,\n"
"  fetchFromGitHub,\n"
"}:\n"
"\n"
"stdenv.mkDerivation {\n"
"  pname = \"icat\";\n"
"  version = \"v0.5\";\n"
"\n"
"  src = fetchFromGitHub {\n"
"    owner = \"atextor\";\n"
"    repo = \"icat\";\n"
"    rev = \"v0.5\";\n"
"    sha256 = \"0wyy2ksxp95vnh71ybj1bbmqd5ggp13x3mk37pzr99ljs9awy8ka\";\n"
"  };\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:332
msgid "Missing dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:334
msgid ""
"Running `nix-build` with the new `icat` attribute, an entirely new issue is "
"reported:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/packaging-existing-software.md:336
msgid ""
"$ nix-build -A icat\n"
"these 2 derivations will be built:\n"
"  /nix/store/86q9x927hsyyzfr4lcqirmsbimysi6mb-source.drv\n"
"  /nix/store/l5wz9inkvkf0qhl8kpl39vpg2xfm2qpy-icat.drv\n"
"...\n"
"error: builder for '/nix/store/l5wz9inkvkf0qhl8kpl39vpg2xfm2qpy-icat.drv' "
"failed with exit code 2;\n"
"       last 10 log lines:\n"
"       >                  from /nix/store/hkj250rjsvxcbr31fr1v81cv88cdfp4l-"
"glibc-2.37-8-dev/include/stdio.h:27,\n"
"       >                  from icat.c:31:\n"
"       > /nix/store/hkj250rjsvxcbr31fr1v81cv88cdfp4l-glibc-2.37-8-dev/"
"include/features.h:195:3: warning: #warning \"_BSD_SOURCE and _SVID_SOURCE "
"are deprecated, use _DEFAULT_SOURCE\" [8;;https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc/"
